{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "CodeGuard",
          "version": "1.0.0",
          "informationUri": "https://github.com/your-org/codeguard",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "javascript.lang.security.audit.sqli.node-mysql-sqli.node-mysql-sqli",
              "name": "node-mysql-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating an `input` variable (derived from `req.query.id`) into the `WHERE` clause. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary SQL code, bypassing authentication, extracting sensitive data, or manipulating the database."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating an `input` variable (derived from `req.query.id`) into the `WHERE` clause. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary SQL code, bypassing authentication, extracting sensitive data, or manipulating the database."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.security.audit.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage.express-check-csurf-middleware-usage",
              "name": "express-check-csurf-middleware-usage",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not appear to implement Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection middleware. Without proper CSRF tokens or other validation for state-changing operations (like POST, PUT, DELETE), an attacker could craft a malicious website that forces authenticated users to unknowingly submit requests to the application, performing unauthorized actions on their behalf."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not appear to implement Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection middleware. Without proper CSRF tokens or other validation for state-changing operations (like POST, PUT, DELETE), an attacker could craft a malicious website that forces authenticated users to unknowingly submit requests to the application, performing unauthorized actions on their behalf."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "INFO",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.mysql.node-mysql-hardcoded-secret.node-mysql-hardcoded-secret",
              "name": "node-mysql-hardcoded-secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Database credentials, specifically the password (`DB_PASSWORD`), are hard-coded directly within the application's source code. This is a severe security risk as it exposes sensitive authentication information. If the source code repository is compromised, or the application bundle is reverse-engineered, attackers can gain direct access to the database."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Database credentials, specifically the password (`DB_PASSWORD`), are hard-coded directly within the application's source code. This is a severe security risk as it exposes sensitive authentication information. If the source code repository is compromised, or the application bundle is reverse-engineered, attackers can gain direct access to the database."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.mysql.express-mysql-sqli.express-mysql-sqli",
              "name": "express-mysql-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query using string concatenation with the `id` variable, which is directly obtained from `req.query.id`. This is highly vulnerable to SQL injection, as an attacker can inject malicious SQL commands into the `id` parameter, leading to unauthorized data access, manipulation, or denial of service."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query using string concatenation with the `id` variable, which is directly obtained from `req.query.id`. This is highly vulnerable to SQL injection, as an attacker can inject malicious SQL commands into the `id` parameter, leading to unauthorized data access, manipulation, or denial of service."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.express-child-process.express-child-process",
              "name": "express-child-process",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly executes a system command using `child_process.exec` where the `command` variable is taken directly from user input (`req.query.cmd`). This is a critical command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly executes a system command using `child_process.exec` where the `command` variable is taken directly from user input (`req.query.cmd`). This is a critical command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.lang.security.detect-child-process.detect-child-process",
              "name": "detect-child-process",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly passes `req.query.cmd` to the `child_process.exec()` function without any sanitization or validation. This creates a severe command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands with the privileges of the Node.js application."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly passes `req.query.cmd` to the `child_process.exec()` function without any sanitization or validation. This creates a severe command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands with the privileges of the Node.js application."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "ERROR",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.security.injection.raw-html-format.raw-html-format",
              "name": "raw-html-format",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "User-controlled input from `req.query.q` is directly embedded into the HTML response body (`<h1>...</h1>`) without proper HTML encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or client-side scripts, leading to a reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "User-controlled input from `req.query.q` is directly embedded into the HTML response body (`<h1>...</h1>`) without proper HTML encoding. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or client-side scripts, leading to a reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_cross_site_scripting",
              "name": "javascript_express_cross_site_scripting",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This finding indicates the same reflected XSS vulnerability as Finding 2. The `req.query.q` parameter is unsafely concatenated into the HTML response, allowing an attacker to inject malicious scripts. This can lead to client-side attacks such as session hijacking or arbitrary content manipulation."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This finding indicates the same reflected XSS vulnerability as Finding 2. The `req.query.q` parameter is unsafely concatenated into the HTML response, allowing an attacker to inject malicious scripts. This can lead to client-side attacks such as session hijacking or arbitrary content manipulation."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.express-fs-filename.express-fs-filename",
              "name": "express-fs-filename",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly uses `req.query.file` as the file path in `fs.readFile()` without proper validation or sanitization. This vulnerability, known as Path Traversal (or Directory Traversal), allows an attacker to manipulate the input (e.g., using `../` sequences) to read arbitrary files outside the intended directory, including sensitive system files."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly uses `req.query.file` as the file path in `fs.readFile()` without proper validation or sanitization. This vulnerability, known as Path Traversal (or Directory Traversal), allows an attacker to manipulate the input (e.g., using `../` sequences) to read arbitrary files outside the intended directory, including sensitive system files."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.jsonwebtoken.security.jwt-hardcode.hardcoded-jwt-secret",
              "name": "hardcoded-jwt-secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret, `'secret'`, is hard-coded directly in the source code. Hard-coding cryptographic secrets is a critical security vulnerability because if the source code is ever exposed (e.g., in a public repository, through a breach), an attacker can easily learn the secret. With the secret, an attacker can forge valid JWTs, bypass authentication, and potentially gain unauthorized access to any user account or privileged functionality."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The JWT signing secret, `'secret'`, is hard-coded directly in the source code. Hard-coding cryptographic secrets is a critical security vulnerability because if the source code is ever exposed (e.g., in a public repository, through a breach), an attacker can easily learn the secret. With the secret, an attacker can forge valid JWTs, bypass authentication, and potentially gain unauthorized access to any user account or privileged functionality."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "WARNING",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.jsonwebtoken.security.jwt-none-alg.jwt-none-alg",
              "name": "jwt-none-alg",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The `jwt.verify` function is explicitly configured to accept the `none` algorithm, effectively bypassing all integrity checks of the JWT token. The `none` algorithm means there is no signature to verify, allowing an attacker to craft any token payload (e.g., impersonating any user, elevating privileges) by setting the 'alg' header to 'none' and the application will validate it as legitimate."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The `jwt.verify` function is explicitly configured to accept the `none` algorithm, effectively bypassing all integrity checks of the JWT token. The `none` algorithm means there is no signature to verify, allowing an attacker to craft any token payload (e.g., impersonating any user, elevating privileges) by setting the 'alg' header to 'none' and the application will validate it as legitimate."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "ERROR",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript.express.mongodb.express-mongo-nosqli.express-mongo-nosqli",
              "name": "express-mongo-nosqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The `mongoose.model('User').findOne` query constructs its conditions directly from user-supplied `req.body.username` and `req.body.password`. An attacker can inject NoSQL operators (e.g., `$gt`, `$ne`, `$or`) into these fields within the request body, potentially bypassing authentication by manipulating the query to always evaluate to true or to match an unintended user."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The `mongoose.model('User').findOne` query constructs its conditions directly from user-supplied `req.body.username` and `req.body.password`. An attacker can inject NoSQL operators (e.g., `$gt`, `$ne`, `$or`) into these fields within the request body, potentially bypassing authentication by manipulating the query to always evaluate to true or to match an unintended user."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Semgrep",
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_express_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The secret used to sign JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) is hardcoded as `'secret'`. This is a critical security flaw because if an attacker discovers this secret (which is trivial if the code is accessible or guessed due to its weakness), they can forge valid JWTs for any user, effectively bypassing authentication and authorization mechanisms. This could allow them to impersonate other users, including administrators, and gain unauthorized access to the application's functionalities and data. The message also points out \"no expiry,\" which exacerbates the issue as forged tokens would never expire."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The secret used to sign JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) is hardcoded as `'secret'`. This is a critical security flaw because if an attacker discovers this secret (which is trivial if the code is accessible or guessed due to its weakness), they can forge valid JWTs for any user, effectively bypassing authentication and authorization mechanisms. This could allow them to impersonate other users, including administrators, and gain unauthorized access to the application's functionalities and data. The message also points out \"no expiry,\" which exacerbates the issue as forged tokens would never expire."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_nosql_injection",
              "name": "javascript_express_nosql_injection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly parses user-supplied input from `req.query.filter` as a JSON object and uses it as a filter for a Mongoose `find` query. This allows an attacker to inject malicious NoSQL query operators, such as `$where`, `$ne`, `$gt`, etc., to manipulate the query logic. An attacker can bypass authentication, access sensitive information they shouldn't have access to, or even perform denial-of-service attacks by constructing complex or infinite loop queries."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly parses user-supplied input from `req.query.filter` as a JSON object and uses it as a filter for a Mongoose `find` query. This allows an attacker to inject malicious NoSQL query operators, such as `$where`, `$ne`, `$gt`, etc., to manipulate the query logic. An attacker can bypass authentication, access sensitive information they shouldn't have access to, or even perform denial-of-service attacks by constructing complex or infinite loop queries."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
              "name": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the value of `req.query.cmd` from user input and passes it to the `exec` function, which executes operating system commands. This is a severe command injection vulnerability. An attacker can inject arbitrary shell commands by appending them to the `cmd` parameter using shell metacharacters (e.g., `&`, `|`, `&&`, `||`, `;`). This allows them to execute any command on the server, potentially leading to remote code execution, data exfiltration, system compromise, or denial-of-service."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application directly takes the value of `req.query.cmd` from user input and passes it to the `exec` function, which executes operating system commands. This is a severe command injection vulnerability. An attacker can inject arbitrary shell commands by appending them to the `cmd` parameter using shell metacharacters (e.g., `&`, `|`, `&&`, `||`, `;`). This allows them to execute any command on the server, potentially leading to remote code execution, data exfiltration, system compromise, or denial-of-service."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A Stripe API key (`sk_test_123456789abcdef`) is hardcoded directly in the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability as it allows anyone with access to the code (e.g., through a public repository or a compromise) to obtain and potentially misuse the key. Even a test key indicates poor security practice that can extend to production keys."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A Stripe API key (`sk_test_123456789abcdef`) is hardcoded directly in the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability as it allows anyone with access to the code (e.g., through a public repository or a compromise) to obtain and potentially misuse the key. Even a test key indicates poor security practice that can extend to production keys."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "CRITICAL",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer",
                  "Gitleaks"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_lang_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A database password (`DB_PASSWORD = 'SuperSecretPassword123'`) is hardcoded directly in the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability as it allows anyone with access to the code to obtain the database credentials, potentially leading to unauthorized access, data theft, or data corruption."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A database password (`DB_PASSWORD = 'SuperSecretPassword123'`) is hardcoded directly in the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability as it allows anyone with access to the code to obtain the database credentials, potentially leading to unauthorized access, data theft, or data corruption."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_jwt_hardcoded_secret",
              "name": "javascript_lang_jwt_hardcoded_secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application signs JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) using a weak, hard-coded secret string (`'secret'`). This makes the JWTs highly vulnerable to brute-force or dictionary attacks, allowing an attacker to guess the secret and forge valid tokens. Additionally, the lack of an `expiresIn` option means tokens never expire, increasing the window of opportunity for attackers if a token is ever compromised."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application signs JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) using a weak, hard-coded secret string (`'secret'`). This makes the JWTs highly vulnerable to brute-force or dictionary attacks, allowing an attacker to guess the secret and forge valid tokens. Additionally, the lack of an `expiresIn` option means tokens never expire, increasing the window of opportunity for attackers if a token is ever compromised."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_sql_injection",
              "name": "javascript_lang_sql_injection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`input`, originating from `req.query.id`) into the query string without any sanitization or parameterization. This allows an attacker to inject malicious SQL code, altering the query's intent."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`input`, originating from `req.query.id`) into the query string without any sanitization or parameterization. This allows an attacker to inject malicious SQL code, altering the query's intent."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_server_side_request_forgery",
              "name": "javascript_express_server_side_request_forgery",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application fetches a URL directly from user input (`req.query.url`) using `axios.get()`. This allows an attacker to control the destination of the HTTP request made by the server. An attacker can direct the server to make requests to internal network resources, cloud metadata APIs, or other services that are not publicly accessible, potentially exposing sensitive information or performing unauthorized actions."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application fetches a URL directly from user input (`req.query.url`) using `axios.get()`. This allows an attacker to control the destination of the HTTP request made by the server. An attacker can direct the server to make requests to internal network resources, cloud metadata APIs, or other services that are not publicly accessible, potentially exposing sensitive information or performing unauthorized actions."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_http_url_using_user_input",
              "name": "javascript_lang_http_url_using_user_input",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) because it constructs an HTTP POST request using a URL directly provided by the user in the request body (`req.body.url`). An attacker can manipulate this URL to make the server send requests to arbitrary internal or external systems, potentially bypassing network firewalls, probing internal services, or accessing sensitive data."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) because it constructs an HTTP POST request using a URL directly provided by the user in the request body (`req.body.url`). An attacker can manipulate this URL to make the server send requests to arbitrary internal or external systems, potentially bypassing network firewalls, probing internal services, or accessing sensitive data."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_non_literal_fs_filename",
              "name": "javascript_lang_non_literal_fs_filename",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Local File Inclusion (LFI) and Path Traversal because it uses user-controlled input (`req.query.file`) directly as a filename for `fs.readFile` without any sanitization or validation. This allows an attacker to specify arbitrary file paths using directory traversal sequences (e.g., `../`) to read sensitive files outside the intended directory."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Local File Inclusion (LFI) and Path Traversal because it uses user-controlled input (`req.query.file`) directly as a filename for `fs.readFile` without any sanitization or validation. This allows an attacker to specify arbitrary file paths using directory traversal sequences (e.g., `../`) to read sensitive files outside the intended directory."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_raw_html_using_user_input",
              "name": "javascript_lang_raw_html_using_user_input",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) because it directly embeds unsanitized user input (`req.query.q`) into the HTML response. This allows an attacker to inject malicious HTML or JavaScript code that will be executed by the victim's browser when they visit a specially crafted URL."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The application is vulnerable to Reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) because it directly embeds unsanitized user input (`req.query.q`) into the HTML response. This allows an attacker to inject malicious HTML or JavaScript code that will be executed by the victim's browser when they visit a specially crafted URL."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_helmet_missing",
              "name": "javascript_express_helmet_missing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not utilize Helmet middleware. Helmet is a collection of 15 smaller middleware functions that set various HTTP headers to help protect the application from well-known web vulnerabilities like XSS, clickjacking, insecure connections, and more. Without Helmet, these security headers are not configured by default, potentially exposing users to client-side attacks."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The Express application does not utilize Helmet middleware. Helmet is a collection of 15 smaller middleware functions that set various HTTP headers to help protect the application from well-known web vulnerabilities like XSS, clickjacking, insecure connections, and more. Without Helmet, these security headers are not configured by default, potentially exposing users to client-side attacks."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
              "name": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "By default, Express applications include an `X-Powered-By: Express` header in their HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server technology stack, which can be leveraged by attackers to identify known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. Removing this header is a security best practice that makes it slightly harder for attackers to fingerprint the server."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "By default, Express applications include an `X-Powered-By: Express` header in their HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server technology stack, which can be leveraged by attackers to identify known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. Removing this header is a security best practice that makes it slightly harder for attackers to fingerprint the server."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "javascript_lang_observable_timing",
              "name": "javascript_lang_observable_timing",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This finding identifies a critical timing attack vulnerability. The `if (token === storedToken)` comparison uses a standard string equality operator. Such operators often short-circuit, meaning they stop comparing characters as soon as a mismatch is found. This results in the comparison taking slightly different amounts of time depending on where in the string the first differing character is located. An attacker can precisely measure these subtle timing differences in the server's response to infer the secret `storedToken` character by character."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "This finding identifies a critical timing attack vulnerability. The `if (token === storedToken)` comparison uses a standard string equality operator. Such operators often short-circuit, meaning they stop comparing characters as soon as a mismatch is found. This results in the comparison taking slightly different amounts of time depending on where in the string the first differing character is located. An attacker can precisely measure these subtle timing differences in the server's response to infer the secret `storedToken` character by character."
              },
              "helpUri": "https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/",
              "properties": {
                "severity": "HIGH",
                "tags": [
                  "Bearer"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "results": [
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.lang.security.audit.sqli.node-mysql-sqli.node-mysql-sqli",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating an `input` variable (derived from `req.query.id`) into the `WHERE` clause. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary SQL code, bypassing authentication, extracting sensitive data, or manipulating the database.\n\nExploit: If an attacker provides `input` as `' OR '1'='1`, the query becomes `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '' OR '1'='1'`, which would return all users. If `input` is `' LIMIT 1; DROP TABLE users; --`, it could delete the `users` table.\n\nFix: Using a parameterized query ensures that the `input` value is treated as data, not executable SQL code, preventing SQL injection. The database driver properly escapes the input, neutralizing any malicious SQL fragments."
          },
          "locations": [
