            "confidenceLevel": "HIGH",
            "detectedBy": [
              "Semgrep"
            ],
            "autoFixable": false,
            "issueId": "CG-005"
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.lang.security.detect-child-process.detect-child-process",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly passes `req.query.cmd` to the `child_process.exec()` function without any sanitization or validation. This creates a severe command injection vulnerability, allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands with the privileges of the Node.js application.\n\nExploit: An attacker can send a request like `/run?cmd=ls%20-la` to list directory contents, or `/run?cmd=rm%20-rf%20/` to delete files (if permissions allow). More complex attacks could involve chaining commands using shell metacharacters such as `cmd=cat%20/etc/passwd%3B%20sleep%2010`.\n\nFix: The fix eliminates the direct execution of user-supplied commands. Instead, it implements a strict whitelist for allowed commands (`cmdName`) and uses `child_process.execFile()`. `execFile()` safely passes arguments as an array, preventing shell interpretation and command injection. Additionally, any user-provided arguments are strictly validated using a regular expression to ensure they do not contain malicious characters or path traversal sequences."
          },
          "locations": [
