        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.express-fs-filename.express-fs-filename",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly uses `req.query.file` as the file path in `fs.readFile()` without proper validation or sanitization. This vulnerability, known as Path Traversal (or Directory Traversal), allows an attacker to manipulate the input (e.g., using `../` sequences) to read arbitrary files outside the intended directory, including sensitive system files.\n\nExploit: An attacker can request `/read?file=../../../../etc/passwd` to retrieve the system's password file, or `/read?file=../../../../app/config.js` to access application configuration or source code files.\n\nFix: The fix establishes a `baseDir` for allowed file access. It rigorously validates the user-supplied `requestedFile` to prevent path traversal sequences (`..`) and absolute paths. It then uses `path.join()` to safely construct the full file path. Most importantly, it verifies that the final resolved `filePath` *remains strictly within* the defined `baseDir`, preventing any attempts to access files outside the authorized directory. This combination of validation and canonicalization effectively mitigates path traversal."
          },
          "locations": [
