          "ruleId": "javascript.express.mongodb.express-mongo-nosqli.express-mongo-nosqli",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[HIGH] The `mongoose.model('User').findOne` query constructs its conditions directly from user-supplied `req.body.username` and `req.body.password`. An attacker can inject NoSQL operators (e.g., `$gt`, `$ne`, `$or`) into these fields within the request body, potentially bypassing authentication by manipulating the query to always evaluate to true or to match an unintended user.\n\nExploit: An attacker can send a login request with a crafted JSON payload like `{\"username\": {\"$ne\": null}, \"password\": {\"$ne\": null}}`. Depending on the MongoDB query parsing and application logic, this could result in the query matching the first user found (or any user where both fields are not null) and logging the attacker in without knowing the correct credentials. Another example is `username=admin&password={\"$gt\": \"\"}` which might log in as 'admin' without the correct password.\n\nFix: User input should never be directly used to construct MongoDB query objects, especially for authentication. Instead, first fetch the user by a non-sensitive identifier like `username`. Then, securely compare the provided password (after hashing) with the stored password. For other queries, strictly validate and sanitize all user inputs to ensure they only contain expected data types and values, escaping any special characters or operators that could be interpreted by MongoDB as commands."
          },
