        {
          "ruleId": "javascript.express.mysql.express-mysql-sqli.express-mysql-sqli",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The `username` and `password` values, derived directly from `req.body`, are unsafely concatenated into an `INSERT` SQL query string. This allows an attacker to inject malicious SQL code by crafting specially designed `username` or `password` inputs. When these inputs are processed by the database, the injected code will be executed, potentially leading to unauthorized data manipulation, bypassing authentication, or executing arbitrary database commands.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a POST request to `/register` with the following body:\n`{ \"username\": \"admin', 'pwned'); --\", \"password\": \"any_password\" }`\nThe resulting SQL query would become approximately:\n`INSERT INTO users VALUES ('admin', 'pwned'); --', 'any_password')`\nThis would insert an 'admin' user with 'pwned' as password, and the rest of the original query after `--` would be ignored. More severe injections could delete tables or modify other data depending on the context.\n\nFix: Instead of concatenating user input directly into the SQL string, parameterized queries (using `?` placeholders) should be used. The values are then passed as a separate array to the `query` method. The MySQL driver will correctly escape and sanitize these values before executing the query, preventing any injected SQL code from being interpreted as commands. This strictly separates SQL commands from user-supplied data."
          },
