        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_nosql_injection",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly parses user-supplied input from `req.query.filter` as a JSON object and uses it as a filter for a Mongoose `find` query. This allows an attacker to inject malicious NoSQL query operators, such as `$where`, `$ne`, `$gt`, etc., to manipulate the query logic. An attacker can bypass authentication, access sensitive information they shouldn't have access to, or even perform denial-of-service attacks by constructing complex or infinite loop queries.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a GET request like:\n`GET /users/search?filter={\"username\":{\"$ne\":null}}`\nThis query would retrieve all users where the username is not null, effectively bypassing any intended filters to list specific users. A more dangerous example using `$where` could be:\n`GET /users/search?filter={\"username\":{\"$where\":\"function() { return (new Date()).getTime() % 100000 === 0; }\"}}`\nThis would execute a JavaScript function for every document, potentially leading to a denial-of-service by consuming excessive server resources.\n\nFix: Instead of directly using user-supplied JSON as a query object, the application must strictly validate and sanitize the input. This involves explicitly defining allowed query parameters and operators (whitelisting). For simple use cases, only allow specific fields to be queried and ensure their values match expected types (e.g., strings, numbers). More complex queries should be constructed using a whitelist of allowed operators and carefully validated input, or a robust query builder that prevents injection."
          },
