            "text": "[CRITICAL] A Stripe API key (`sk_test_123456789abcdef`) is hardcoded directly in the source code. This is a critical security vulnerability as it allows anyone with access to the code (e.g., through a public repository or a compromise) to obtain and potentially misuse the key. Even a test key indicates poor security practice that can extend to production keys.\n\nExploit: An attacker gains access to the source code (e.g., via a public GitHub repository or a leaked build). They extract the `sk_test_123456789abcdef` key and can then use it to make requests to the Stripe API on behalf of the application, potentially manipulating test data or gaining insight into the Stripe integration. If a production key were similarly hardcoded, it would allow full control over the Stripe account.\n\nFix: API keys should always be loaded from environment variables (e.g., `process.env.STRIPE_API_KEY`) or a secure configuration management system at runtime. This prevents sensitive information from being exposed in the codebase and allows for easy rotation and different keys for different environments."
