          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[CRITICAL] The application constructs a SQL query by directly concatenating user-controlled input (`input`, originating from `req.query.id`) into the query string without any sanitization or parameterization. This allows an attacker to inject malicious SQL code, altering the query's intent.\n\nExploit: If an attacker sends a request like `GET /users?id=1%20OR%201=1`, the `input` variable becomes `\"1 OR 1=1\"`. The resulting query will be `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1 OR 1=1`, which will return all users, bypassing intended authorization or filtering. More maliciously, `id=1; DROP TABLE users;` could delete the `users` table.\n\nFix: To prevent SQL injection, always use parameterized queries (prepared statements). This method separates the SQL query structure from user-supplied data, ensuring that the input is treated as literal values rather than executable SQL code, even if it contains malicious characters."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/services/userService.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 13
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "To prevent SQL injection, always use parameterized queries (prepared statements). This method separates the SQL query structure from user-supplied data, ensuring that the input is treated as literal values rather than executable SQL code, even if it contains malicious characters."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
