        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_server_side_request_forgery",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "[HIGH] The application fetches a URL directly from user input (`req.query.url`) using `axios.get()`. This allows an attacker to control the destination of the HTTP request made by the server. An attacker can direct the server to make requests to internal network resources, cloud metadata APIs, or other services that are not publicly accessible, potentially exposing sensitive information or performing unauthorized actions.\n\nExploit: An attacker can provide an internal IP address or a cloud metadata endpoint as the URL. For instance, `GET /fetch?url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/` to access AWS instance metadata, or `GET /fetch?url=http://localhost:8080/admin` to access an internal admin panel that might not be directly exposed to the internet.\n\nFix: To prevent SSRF, never directly use user-supplied URLs for server-side requests without strict validation. Implement a whitelist of allowed domains and protocols. Thoroughly parse and validate the URL to ensure it points only to intended, safe external resources and cannot target internal networks, `localhost`, or arbitrary file schemes."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
