        {
          "ruleId": "javascript_express_reduce_fingerprint",
          "level": "note",
          "message": {
            "text": "[LOW] By default, Express applications include an `X-Powered-By: Express` header in their HTTP responses. This header reveals information about the server technology stack, which can be leveraged by attackers to identify known vulnerabilities specific to Express or Node.js versions. Removing this header is a security best practice that makes it slightly harder for attackers to fingerprint the server.\n\nExploit: An attacker could use network scanning tools or simply inspect HTTP response headers to discover the `X-Powered-By: Express` header. If a known vulnerability exists in a specific version of Express, this information could guide the attacker in targeting the application. This is a form of security by obscurity, making reconnaissance slightly more difficult.\n\nFix: The fix disables the `X-Powered-By` header by calling `app.disable('x-powered-by')` immediately after initializing the Express application. This removes the default header that reveals the server technology (Express), thereby reducing the server's fingerprint and making it slightly more difficult for attackers to identify and target specific vulnerabilities associated with the framework."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                  "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 24
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fixes": [
            {
              "description": {
                "text": "The fix disables the `X-Powered-By` header by calling `app.disable('x-powered-by')` immediately after initializing the Express application. This removes the default header that reveals the server technology (Express), thereby reducing the server's fingerprint and making it slightly more difficult for attackers to identify and target specific vulnerabilities associated with the framework."
              },
              "artifactChanges": [
                {
                  "artifactLocation": {
                    "uri": "src/test-vuln-2.js",
                    "uriBaseId": "%SRCROOT%"
                  },
                  "replacements": [
